        #     "body": "{\"id\": \"123\", \"metadata\": \"{\\\"documentName\\\": \\\"eoir_coverletter_for_i589_form\\\", \\\"documentType\\\": \\\"eoir_coverletter\\\", \\\"document\\\": \\\"I-589 Form\\\", \\\"caseId\\\": \\\"242\\\", \\\"userId\\\": \\\"10\\\", \\\"client\\\": {\\\"lastName\\\": \\\"Yang\\\", \\\"firstName\\\": \\\"Zhao\\\", \\\"dateOfBirth\\\": \\\"09/03/1985\\\", \\\"countryOfOrigin\\\": \\\"China\\\", \\\"gender\\\": \\\"Female\\\", \\\"residential_address\\\": \\\"1 Shore Lane APT1510 Jersey City, US-0-NJ 07310\\\", \\\"alienNumber\\\": \\\"64819471111\\\", \\\"additionalApplicants\\\": \\\"\\\", \\\"additionalApplicantAlienNumber\\\": \\\"111-111-111, 22-222-22332\\\", \\\"personalStatement\\\": \\\"My name is Zhao Yang, holding a Chinese passport with the number SE0000000, female, born in Chenghua, Guangdong, China on September 3, 1985, and I am 39 years old this year. I entered the United States from recent entry location on July 11, 2024, under the status of B1. I have a fluency in English and also speak Japanese.\\\\n\\\\nI arrived in the U.S. seeking asylum based on religious and national origin persecution. My escape from Pingdingshan City, Henan Province, China, was provoked by the removal of religious and cultural symbols from my residence by local authorities on November 19, 2019. This oppressive act underscored the bigotry and intolerance I faced due to my faith and background. The escalating threat of continued mistreatment and potential arrest prompted my immediate departure to the U.S.\\\\n\\\\nThe grim reality of persecution in my home country leaves me no choice but to seek refuge here. The heinous actions of the authorities only foreshadow the grave danger awaiting me if I were to return. The torment and discrimination I endured in China have stripped me of safety and freedom. The urgency of my plea for asylum rests upon the stark certainty of relentless persecution upon my return.\\\"}, \\\"attorney\\\": {\\\"lastName\\\": \\\